**World Health Assembly Sixty-Fourth – Daily Bulletin: 27th of May 2023**

The World Health Assembly today endorsed a global strategy on infection prevention and control (IPC) – the first of its kind – supported by champions like the WHO and its partners. The strategy provides evidence-based approaches for Member States to increase protection against healthcare-associated infections (HAIs), which pose a significant threat to patient safety within health service delivery systems. Recent COVID-19 outbreaks and other major outbreaks such as Ebola, Marburg Virus Disease, and Sudan Virus have severely weakened IPC systems in all countries.

The strategy sets a target: by 2030, all people using or providing health services are protected from infections. Its two main pillars are: to prevent infections in health services; to ensure that IPC programs are established and implemented; and to lead IPC efforts with communities and other sectors. The strategy is based on a tiered approach that is evidence-informed and not overly complex, like the steps for the right to health, which is led, and must promote equity and protection. The global IPC strategy will be implemented alongside the global health security and action plan on antimicrobial resistance, which will be developed in 2023-2024.

**Document EB152/9 – Report on the Global Strategy on Infection Prevention and Control, Report by the Director-General on Infection Prevention and Control**

The World Health Assembly today endorsed a decision to strengthen health system resilience. The resilience of health systems plays a critical role in ensuring the well-being of patients and reducing mortality rates. It also supports maternal and child health and the right to work and education. This decision aims to address the challenges in resilience, including:

*   To reduce barriers to resilience during health emergencies and disasters, allocating resources, implementing and supporting innovation and technology;
*   To ensure that countries have the resources to respond to resilience needs related to digital health technologies due to health vulnerabilities;
*   To ensure that people in vulnerable situations have access to resilience services that are appropriate and affordable, addressing digital health technologies;
*   To address the shortage of resilience workers to meet the needs of urban populations.

This decision outlines several steps that the WHO Secretariat will take, including:

*   Preparing a report by the end of 2026 with an assessment of Member States’ progress in meeting resilience needs;
*   Developing resources and tools to support the implementation of resilience services in 2023;
*   Ensuring that WHO procures the necessary equipment to support Member States in the development of digital health technologies and equipment;
*   Supporting Member States to integrate resilience and digital health technologies into their health programs and address their vulnerabilities.

The WHO Secretariat will report on the progress of implementing this decision to the Assembly in 2026, 2028, and 2030.

