A partnership under the leadership is crucial for global progress towards the SDGs related to health. A new momentum report was launched today by 13 organizations committed to the Global Action Plan on Healthy Lives and Wellbeing for All (SDG3 GAP). The report, titled "What worked? What didn't? What's next?" reviews four years of partnership work from various organizations examining what has and hasn't worked to foster strong partnerships and support national progress towards health-related SDGs. This year marks the midpoint of the SDGs, but the entire world is still working to achieve those global targets. Since its launch in 2019, SDG3 GAP has facilitated the mobilization of new partnerships among organizations committed to key areas such as financial investment and primary healthcare programs, among others. Approximately 67 countries have participated in one or more of the SDG3 GAP action tracks. Significant progress has been made, but there is still a path to follow to accelerate the way various organizations work together to support countries. "We must listen to what countries are telling us and build partnerships based on their priorities," said Dr Tedros Adhanom Ghebreyesus, WHO Director-General and Chair of the SDG3 GAP Leadership Group. "I commend our partners for their collaboration and the honest self-reflection contained in this report."

The report highlights six key findings to ensure countries benefit from readily available support and to understand the contributions made within SDG3 GAP. These include: advancing the SDG3 GAP health equity lens with a review of the progress of Member States on how partnerships are being implemented at the country level and identifying areas for improvement; accelerating the GAP overall, including a call for partnership; strengthening support for robust partnerships at the country level on primary healthcare and to develop new terminology such as telehealth programs; jointly developing new approaches at the country level, such as a framework for engagement; bringing in more non-state actors; and working with Member States to strengthen the impact of partnerships through country leadership, government stewardship, and financial investment to support partnerships. The report’s key findings will be incorporated into the agenda of the High-Level Political Dialogue on the Global Health Crisis being held in November 2023. The upcoming months are critical for joint action by Member States and various organizations to find ways to ensure the mobilization of resources to accelerate progress towards the SDGs related to health in the second decade of the SDGs. In short: SDG3 GAP describes how 13 organizations that are committed are leveraging new ways of working, building on past partnership successes, and pooling their support for country programs and country-led initiatives. The organizations committed to SDG3 GAP include Gavi, the Vaccine Alliance; The Global Fund for Women, Children and Adolescents (GFF); The Global Fund to Fight AIDS, Tuberculosis and Malaria; The International Labour Organization (ILO);
